    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "For the case of the block mentioned in the linked issue, `methodNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing)` is true, but `fieldNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing)` is false.\r\n\r\nThis means that `findAndMergeSuperMaps(parentThing)` is not called. Then, when the following code runs\r\n```java\r\nif (methodNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing))\r\n{\r\n\tmethodMap.putAll(methodNameMaps.get(parentThing));\r\n}\r\nif (fieldNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing))\r\n{\r\n\tfieldMap.putAll(fieldNameMaps.get(parentThing));\r\n}\r\n```\r\nas `fieldNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing)` is false, the field map will not inherit entries from the parent class.\r\n\r\nThis causes `Block` fields referenced in the class to not be deofuscated, which causes a `NoSuchFieldError` to occur.",

    "created_at": "2018-05-01T16:43:31Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-05-01T16:43:31Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Will try to address a couple of the points mentioned.\r\n\r\nThe \"top level\" map keys are class names. The corresponding values are maps of (original -> remapped) field/method names.\r\n\r\n`findAndMergeSuperMaps` is called for a class if that class does not have a field/method map associated with it. This will cause those maps to be generated.\r\n\r\nAs mentioned in the first comment, classes can have a method map entry without a field entry in the case that the class is added to both maps (from `mergeSuperMaps`), but subsequently removed from the field map (from `storeMemberFieldMapping`).\r\n\r\nThis will cause subclasses to not inherit that classes' field mappings, as they will not be regenerated.",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "created_at": "2018-04-12T22:47:52Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-04-12T22:47:52Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "For the case of the block mentioned in the linked issue, `methodNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing)` is true, but `fieldNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing)` is false.\r\n\r\nThis means that `findAndMergeSuperMaps(parentThing)` is not called. Then, when the following code runs\r\n```java\r\nif (methodNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing))\r\n{\r\n\tmethodMap.putAll(methodNameMaps.get(parentThing));\r\n}\r\nif (fieldNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing))\r\n{\r\n\tfieldMap.putAll(fieldNameMaps.get(parentThing));\r\n}\r\n```\r\nas `fieldNameMaps.containsKey(parentThing)` is false, the field map will not inherit entries from the parent class.\r\n\r\nThis causes `Block` fields referenced in the class to not be deofuscated, which causes a `NoSuchFieldError` to occur.",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2018-05-01T16:43:31Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-05-01T16:43:31Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Will try to address a couple of the points mentioned.\r\n\r\nThe \"top level\" map keys are class names. The corresponding values are maps of (original -> remapped) field/method names.\r\n\r\n`findAndMergeSuperMaps` is called for a class if that class does not have a field/method map associated with it. This will cause those maps to be generated.\r\n\r\nAs mentioned in the first comment, classes can have a method map entry without a field entry in the case that the class is added to both maps (from `mergeSuperMaps`), but subsequently removed from the field map (from `storeMemberFieldMapping`).\r\n\r\nThis will cause subclasses to not inherit that classes' field mappings, as they will not be regenerated.",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "body": "Found a few more minor bugs.\r\n\r\n1. If a checkbox is disabled then you can tab past it fine you just can't tab _back_ using shift. In the image I can tab from the start to the currently selected checkbox but I can't then go backwards to the shadows dropdown. ![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6791585/49620281-4e046180-fa14-11e8-89bd-046ec698f414.png).\r\n2. It takes two key presses of `tab` before tabbing starts. I don't know if this is intentional but it's consistent. Simply click empty space to deselect and then press tab once. You should notice nothing happens. If you then press it again it will start tabbing. This occurs when paired with shift as well.\r\n3. If you tab to a checkbox and then scroll the scrollable area the checkbox is visually deselected. This is only visual and you can still toggle via `enter`. This also happens when you click it manually so it _may_ not be your code that's causing it.\r\n4. I still can't get checkboxes to work when using `enter`. This applies to both when I tab to select it or when I click to select it.\r\n5. When I'm using the module selection screen, I can select a module and hence activate it. However I can't then deactivate it. Either via the deactivate button or via `enter` again. Additionally it doesn't visually show as activated. (red empasis added by me) \r\n![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/6791585/49620646-fbc44000-fa15-11e8-8535-766f02812bb9.png). Again, seeing as this also occurs when you select by clicking or pressing select it may not be a result of this PR. This does only occur when you've tabbed at some point in that screen however. I wasn't able to replicate this with further testing nor did I notice anything in the log so I'll just keep an eye out if I can reliably reproduce it.\r\n6. If you tab to select any non-dropdown and then click on a dropdown, [every subsequent keypress gives this in the log](https://hastebin.com/jatepaduxo.txt). It doesn't crash though. This can be reproduced for seemingly any widget, it just changes what it's trying to cast to dropdown\r\n3. _This isn't a bug per se_ but you can tab out of view. It would be nice to have the selected widget always in view.\r\n4. Similarly, _not a bug_ but it would be nice to have tabbing start from the currently selected widget. That seems like it would be more intuitive.\r\n8. _Not a bug_ but would be nice to have UI TextAreas as tab-able along with the sliding selector things.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nI'd be happy to merge this with with only fixing item 4, 6 and the outstanding review comments. Especially for the last three items as well as the visual bugs, they could be moved into an issue and fixed at a later date. That would free you up to work on other tasks if you wanted (So long as you agreed to come back and fix them _eventually_ haha)",

Would need to then also be taken into account for fall damage (a 30m giant able to jump 15 blocks in one go probably shouldn't then die from a 15 block fall)\n\nIt may well be that you need a UI binding to something that'll trigger an event that can be caught by the ES to adjust the player's height dynamically ... somehow. Like we went over on chat there may be some odd interactions with the physics system.\n\nMay need some more tinkering and discussion with those who'd likely know more, like @Josharias @portokaliu, @Flo or @immortius if you can catch him on IRC sometime (the others Slack may work best with)\n\nFor general FYI on justifying this odd feature: I consider it an experimental stepping stone to get into working on grow/shrink potions (hi @xrtariq2594!), or varying the player's height when crouching or even crawling (allow passing through a 1-block height gap, don't allow a sniper to hit a player crouching behind blocks). Some of those may be better handled via temporary modifiers rather than changing height and such directly.\n\nMaybe some gameplay would allow the setting (creative building) while others should be able to block it somehow.\n\nI've got more thoughts on the topic but not enough time, up way too late as it is. But keep up the good work! We need more experts in stuff like this :D\n",

The sky goes black, water disappears, and some weird skysphere-related pattern becomes visible.\n\nWhile I have nothing to base this on I suspect this is probably something simple for a 3d wizard (similar effects have happened before). It appears active across all settings I tried, from minimal to ultra, before or after changing settings in-game. But it would be good to know if anybody else sees it :-)\n\nBlack sky:\n\n![blacksky](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1063833/17838519/716b20ac-679d-11e6-97ca-27abc4c2a539.jpg)\n\nNo Water:\n\n![nowater](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1063833/17838524/7d908890-679d-11e6-9aad-3ca739629051.jpg)\n\nWeird skysphere pattern or something:\n\n![skyspherepattern](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/1063833/17838525/85f1b392-679d-11e6-8fb9-56cb31858b22.jpg)\n\nDouble checked that it seems to be caused by this PR, at least when merged on top of latest develop.\n",

    "created_at": "2016-03-21T21:49:21Z",
    "updated_at": "2016-03-21T21:49:21Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Thank you @pollend for working on this. Indeed it is good to see somebody new venturing in this area of the code. \n\nI haven't had the chance to look into the depths of ShaderLand as I call it, and in particular the relationship between main light in the sky, lights in the 3d world, tone mapping and exposure.\n\nWhat I do notice elsewhere in the code (i.e. WorldRendererImpl - lighting-related methods) is that there are a fair amount of magic numbers and some of the resulting rendering behaviors are not satisfactory. For example, if you place a fire torch in daylight (or four, or 100), it shouldn't actually have any effect on its surroundings because its output should be -completely- swamped by sunlight. On the other hand, the same torch in a dark tunnel could be nearly blinding (via bloom filter) if seen too up close.\n\nWhat I'm worried about is that somewhere there are non-linear calculations or non-linear data fed to the engine and this might be leaving other portions of the engine ineffective even though they are theoretically correct. \n\nI look forward to further work in this field. Also, please stay tuned for some impeding refactoring/documenting of WorldRendererImpl, one of the top level classes of the rendering engine.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "updated_at": "2016-03-22T23:45:16Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Yes, there probably is a lot of data being passed to the GPU every frame even though it hasn't actually changed. Again, I didn't dive much into ShaderLand and I do not know how much of this is avoidable.\n\nYou have to remember that the project founder only wanted to do a feature-rich prototype. I don't think he meant it to be a very high performance engine. He just wanted to implement a bunch of things to see if he could. And he could, but left a prototype, not a production-ready engine. So, that's what you are up against. =)\n\nRegarding your question: if you think they should be exposed do so. Never mind the performance: a few more exposed uniforms won't sink the frame rate. But do try to establish a criteria: why should a uniform be exposed? Should they all be exposed? Should you have a user-case in mind before you expose a uniform? Have some kind of criteria in mind to make sure you make consistent decisions about it.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Thank you @pollend for working on this. Indeed it is good to see somebody new venturing in this area of the code. \n\nI haven't had the chance to look into the depths of ShaderLand as I call it, and in particular the relationship between main light in the sky, lights in the 3d world, tone mapping and exposure.\n\nWhat I do notice elsewhere in the code (i.e. WorldRendererImpl - lighting-related methods) is that there are a fair amount of magic numbers and some of the resulting rendering behaviors are not satisfactory. For example, if you place a fire torch in daylight (or four, or 100), it shouldn't actually have any effect on its surroundings because its output should be -completely- swamped by sunlight. On the other hand, the same torch in a dark tunnel could be nearly blinding (via bloom filter) if seen too up close.\n\nWhat I'm worried about is that somewhere there are non-linear calculations or non-linear data fed to the engine and this might be leaving other portions of the engine ineffective even though they are theoretically correct. \n\nI look forward to further work in this field. Also, please stay tuned for some impeding refactoring/documenting of WorldRendererImpl, one of the top level classes of the rendering engine.\n",

    "body": "this section of the code. It fixed the blinding problem with point lights.\n\n // TODO: Make cutoff a shader parameter\n    const float cutoff= 0.005;\n\n```\n// calculate basic attenuation\nfloat denom = lightDist/1.5 + 1;\nfloat attenuation = 1.0/(denom*denom);\n//float attenuation = clamp (1.0 - ((lightDist * lightDist) / (lightAttenuationRange * lightAttenuationRange)), 0.0, 1.0);\n//float attenuation = 1.0 - (pow (lightDist, lightAttenuationFalloff) / lightAttenuationRange);\n\nattenuation = (attenuation - cutoff)/(1.0-cutoff);\nattenuation = max(attenuation,0);\n\nspecular *= attenuation ;\ncolor *= attenuation * max(dot(lightDir/ lightDist, normal), 0);\n```\n",

    "updated_at": "2016-03-22T23:45:16Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Yes, there probably is a lot of data being passed to the GPU every frame even though it hasn't actually changed. Again, I didn't dive much into ShaderLand and I do not know how much of this is avoidable.\n\nYou have to remember that the project founder only wanted to do a feature-rich prototype. I don't think he meant it to be a very high performance engine. He just wanted to implement a bunch of things to see if he could. And he could, but left a prototype, not a production-ready engine. So, that's what you are up against. =)\n\nRegarding your question: if you think they should be exposed do so. Never mind the performance: a few more exposed uniforms won't sink the frame rate. But do try to establish a criteria: why should a uniform be exposed? Should they all be exposed? Should you have a user-case in mind before you expose a uniform? Have some kind of criteria in mind to make sure you make consistent decisions about it.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "updated_at": "2016-03-21T21:49:21Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Thank you @pollend for working on this. Indeed it is good to see somebody new venturing in this area of the code. \n\nI haven't had the chance to look into the depths of ShaderLand as I call it, and in particular the relationship between main light in the sky, lights in the 3d world, tone mapping and exposure.\n\nWhat I do notice elsewhere in the code (i.e. WorldRendererImpl - lighting-related methods) is that there are a fair amount of magic numbers and some of the resulting rendering behaviors are not satisfactory. For example, if you place a fire torch in daylight (or four, or 100), it shouldn't actually have any effect on its surroundings because its output should be -completely- swamped by sunlight. On the other hand, the same torch in a dark tunnel could be nearly blinding (via bloom filter) if seen too up close.\n\nWhat I'm worried about is that somewhere there are non-linear calculations or non-linear data fed to the engine and this might be leaving other portions of the engine ineffective even though they are theoretically correct. \n\nI look forward to further work in this field. Also, please stay tuned for some impeding refactoring/documenting of WorldRendererImpl, one of the top level classes of the rendering engine.\n",

    "updated_at": "2016-03-22T23:45:16Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Yes, there probably is a lot of data being passed to the GPU every frame even though it hasn't actually changed. Again, I didn't dive much into ShaderLand and I do not know how much of this is avoidable.\n\nYou have to remember that the project founder only wanted to do a feature-rich prototype. I don't think he meant it to be a very high performance engine. He just wanted to implement a bunch of things to see if he could. And he could, but left a prototype, not a production-ready engine. So, that's what you are up against. =)\n\nRegarding your question: if you think they should be exposed do so. Never mind the performance: a few more exposed uniforms won't sink the frame rate. But do try to establish a criteria: why should a uniform be exposed? Should they all be exposed? Should you have a user-case in mind before you expose a uniform? Have some kind of criteria in mind to make sure you make consistent decisions about it.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

Indeed it is good to see somebody new venturing in this area of the code. \n\nI haven't had the chance to look into the depths of ShaderLand as I call it, and in particular the relationship between main light in the sky, lights in the 3d world, tone mapping and exposure.\n\nWhat I do notice elsewhere in the code (i.e. WorldRendererImpl - lighting-related methods) is that there are a fair amount of magic numbers and some of the resulting rendering behaviors are not satisfactory. For example, if you place a fire torch in daylight (or four, or 100), it shouldn't actually have any effect on its surroundings because its output should be -completely- swamped by sunlight. On the other hand, the same torch in a dark tunnel could be nearly blinding (via bloom filter) if seen too up close.\n\nWhat I'm worried about is that somewhere there are non-linear calculations or non-linear data fed to the engine and this might be leaving other portions of the engine ineffective even though they are theoretically correct. \n\nI look forward to further work in this field. Also, please stay tuned for some impeding refactoring/documenting of WorldRendererImpl, one of the top level classes of the rendering engine.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Yes, there probably is a lot of data being passed to the GPU every frame even though it hasn't actually changed. Again, I didn't dive much into ShaderLand and I do not know how much of this is avoidable.\n\nYou have to remember that the project founder only wanted to do a feature-rich prototype. I don't think he meant it to be a very high performance engine. He just wanted to implement a bunch of things to see if he could. And he could, but left a prototype, not a production-ready engine. So, that's what you are up against. =)\n\nRegarding your question: if you think they should be exposed do so. Never mind the performance: a few more exposed uniforms won't sink the frame rate. But do try to establish a criteria: why should a uniform be exposed? Should they all be exposed? Should you have a user-case in mind before you expose a uniform? Have some kind of criteria in mind to make sure you make consistent decisions about it.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> Moved FullRotationFamily to Signalling, though I'm sure it will be copy/pasted to many mods.\n\nThis is an argument for it being in a common module, not being in engine. The point of engine is to provide the minimum required to support the game, not to provide features that are of common or even universal appeal. I know there is a lot of cruft in engine, and we have not always done well at keeping to this principle, but I still feel we should aspire to it.\n\nI suggest we should create a new \"common\" module, siphon anything relevant out of core into it, add your FullRotationFamily, and start maintaining this as a source for commonly useful but piecemeal features, at least until enough stuff builds up that it makes sense to split them out into separate modules.  Would need to come up with some inclusion guidelines along the lines of guava (need to ensure things are commonly useful and not just some neat feature which one person needs).\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2015-06-10T16:41:38Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-06-10T16:41:38Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I now agree with @MarcinSc about taking out Block.getDirection() in favor of the block family implementation of what direction a block is facing.  Using the block family is the only way that modules can attach extra metadata to a particular block (in this case, the facing direction) because the Block class is final.  The Block class should probably keep to the purpose of determining how a block is displayed in the world.\n\nThe other direction we could go is to allow subclasses of Block to be created and returned from the block family.  That would allow creation of a BlockThatFacesADirection class that would then contain the method that returns the direction.  However, I am unsure if that would cause all sorts of other problems in the rest of the engine.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "> Moved FullRotationFamily to Signalling, though I'm sure it will be copy/pasted to many mods.\n\nThis is an argument for it being in a common module, not being in engine. The point of engine is to provide the minimum required to support the game, not to provide features that are of common or even universal appeal. I know there is a lot of cruft in engine, and we have not always done well at keeping to this principle, but I still feel we should aspire to it.\n\nI suggest we should create a new \"common\" module, siphon anything relevant out of core into it, add your FullRotationFamily, and start maintaining this as a source for commonly useful but piecemeal features, at least until enough stuff builds up that it makes sense to split them out into separate modules.  Would need to come up with some inclusion guidelines along the lines of guava (need to ensure things are commonly useful and not just some neat feature which one person needs).\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2015-06-10T16:41:38Z",
    "updated_at": "2015-06-10T16:41:38Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "I now agree with @MarcinSc about taking out Block.getDirection() in favor of the block family implementation of what direction a block is facing.  Using the block family is the only way that modules can attach extra metadata to a particular block (in this case, the facing direction) because the Block class is final.  The Block class should probably keep to the purpose of determining how a block is displayed in the world.\n\nThe other direction we could go is to allow subclasses of Block to be created and returned from the block family.  That would allow creation of a BlockThatFacesADirection class that would then contain the method that returns the direction.  However, I am unsure if that would cause all sorts of other problems in the rest of the engine.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

Moving it back made Gradle work\n\nBuilt it in Jenkins: http://jenkins.movingblocks.net/job/HighlightedBranch/26/\n\nRunning from source and using Faceted Perlin runs great! No crippling lag!     "updated_at": "2013-11-22T03:02:14Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "It sounds like these are not style warnings. For some reason I can see these in the editor, but they're not reported anywhere central in IntelliJ that I can see (maybe I'm missing a configuration option). Ideally I would like to deal with these warnings rather than blanket hide them.\n\nThe varargs warnings (possible heap corruption) are a particular pain. With Java 7, it is expected that methods receiving generic varargs like:\n\n```\nIterable<EntityRef> getEntitiesWith(Class<? extends Component>... componentClasses);\n```\n\nShould he annotated with @SafeVarargs - but this can only be done on final implementing methods. This is supposed to show the developer has consciously ensured they handle the varargs correctly (since the compiler cannot actually determine this).  But since we work through interfaces there's no way to deal with the warning.\n",

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Small update - pushed some initial work to my personal fork including some meant to help out Eclipse. Works out of the box now with no tweaks to the build path needed :-)\n\nThe quirky stuff was due to having to depend on unit tests in the engine for unit tests in modules (if for instance the TerasologyTestingEnvironment was extended). That can be configured fine in Gradle and somewhat in IntelliJ (that's what got us circular dependencies in the past) but causes a broken reference in Eclipse. Putting said unit tests in a completely separate sub-project clarifies the config and makes it work all over.\n\nStill need some more work to then actually figure out where to load natives from in the different scenarios, that was broken previously in several spots even before considering Eclipse. The working directory can differ heavily, especially when also considering solo-module-builds in  Jenkins\n\nhttps://github.com/Cervator/Terasology/commit/06e725af02ef947e2662e9fda4b37d1e584c87f7\n",

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "It sounds like these are not style warnings. For some reason I can see these in the editor, but they're not reported anywhere central in IntelliJ that I can see (maybe I'm missing a configuration option). Ideally I would like to deal with these warnings rather than blanket hide them.\n\nThe varargs warnings (possible heap corruption) are a particular pain. With Java 7, it is expected that methods receiving generic varargs like:\n\n```\nIterable<EntityRef> getEntitiesWith(Class<? extends Component>... componentClasses);\n```\n\nShould he annotated with @SafeVarargs - but this can only be done on final implementing methods. This is supposed to show the developer has consciously ensured they handle the varargs correctly (since the compiler cannot actually determine this).  But since we work through interfaces there's no way to deal with the warning.\n",

    "created_at": "2013-12-26T07:28:56Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-12-26T07:28:56Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Small update - pushed some initial work to my personal fork including some meant to help out Eclipse. Works out of the box now with no tweaks to the build path needed :-)\n\nThe quirky stuff was due to having to depend on unit tests in the engine for unit tests in modules (if for instance the TerasologyTestingEnvironment was extended). That can be configured fine in Gradle and somewhat in IntelliJ (that's what got us circular dependencies in the past) but causes a broken reference in Eclipse. Putting said unit tests in a completely separate sub-project clarifies the config and makes it work all over.\n\nStill need some more work to then actually figure out where to load natives from in the different scenarios, that was broken previously in several spots even before considering Eclipse. The working directory can differ heavily, especially when also considering solo-module-builds in  Jenkins\n\nhttps://github.com/Cervator/Terasology/commit/06e725af02ef947e2662e9fda4b37d1e584c87f7\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  }

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "That test doesn't benchmark most of my changes. The storage format of the chunks has changed though, so it does apply to that part of my changes. \n\nIn my opinion, the benchmark should be changed though, because all the chunks it benchmarks are initialized with zeros, so the benchmark does not tell you anything about the performance of the different chunk stores in a \"real world situation\". Lots of zeros can probably be compressed much faster than actual chunk data like it exists in the game. And it doesn't tell you anything about how good the different chunk stores can compress real chunks, because they only have to compress a big bunch of zeros in the test...\n\nI will take a look at that. And i will implement a benchmark for dense and sparse arrays.\n",

    "created_at": "2013-01-01T19:46:58Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-01-01T20:43:13Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "Hi. Sorry for my absence in the past couple days. I was quite busy.\n\nHope you enjoyd chrismas!\n\n---\n\n@Cervator \nI have put some work into a tiny \"benchmark framework\" to make it easyier to implement benchmarks for terasology.\nIt is located under 'src/dev/java/org/terasology/benchmark/' in my branch simple-sparse-chunk.\n\nOn top of that benchmark framework i have implemented a couple of benchmarks for dense and sparse arrays. There are separate implementations for read and write performance.\n\n---\n\nNow there is one very important thing to be aware of if you want to run the benchmarks for yourself.\nTo get any meaningful results you have to run every benchmark separate. That means, start the vm, run a single benchmark, print the results, shut down the vm.\nOtherwise the results are useless.\n\nFor example: \nIf you would run the read performance benchmarks for 8-bit and 4-bit dense arrays first and then those for the 8-bit and 4-bit sparse arrays, the results would indicate that the sparse arrays perform far worse than the dense arrays.\nOn the other hand, if you would first benchmark the sparse arrays and afterwards the dense arrays, the results would indicate that the dense arrays perform extremely bad compared to the sparse arrays.\n\nI guess, this is because of the runtime jit optimizations the hotspot vm does. This cannot be influenced. The only solution i know for that weird behavior is to run the benchmarks separate.\n\nCurrently, the \"benchmark framework\" does not automate this. I have obtained these results manually. I will think about how to automate this in the future.\n\n---\n\nMy conclusions from the benchmark results are clear. The sparse arrays are equally fast as the dense arrays. So there should be no performance impact at all.\n\nThe results also show that the 4-bit implementations are between 3x and 4x slower than the 8-bit implementations. I think for performance reasons it might be a good idea to use 8-bit arrays instead of 4-bit arrays for sunlight, light and liquid data. The sparse arrays can compress that data much better than the block data anyway.\n\nSo, what do you think? \n\n---\n\n<pre>\nThere are currently 8 benchmarks for the different tera arrays. \nIn the source code they are organized as follows:\n* read performance\n  - dense arrays\n    - 8-bit\n    - 4-bit\n  - sparse arrays\n    - 8-bit\n    - 4-bit\n* write performance\n  - dense arrays\n    - 8-bit\n    - 4-bit\n  - sparse arrays\n    - 8-bit\n    - 4-bit\n</pre>\n\n---\n\n<pre>\nHere are some results:\n***************************************\n* 8-bit dense array read performance  *\n* 31\n2 |        5000 |        310\n3 |       50000 |       3090\n4 |      100000 |       6186\n***************************************\n* 4-bit dense array read performance  *\n*                 vs.     "updated_at": "2013-01-01T20:42:35Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@ahoehma \nSorry for the late answer! Unfortunately its currently impossible to make big changes to the chunk class without breaking existing worlds! To make saved worlds more robust and more persistent its unavoidable to define a file format for chunks. Maybe that could be done using protocol buffers? \n\nAltough, with the new tera arrays i've implemented it is now much easier to make changes to the chunk class without necessarily breaking existing worlds! New kinds of tera arrays can be implemented and used without breaking any existing worlds. If done carefully enough its even possible to switch between existing and new implementations without breaking existing worlds.\n\nAbout the memory stuff. When you press F3 in the game you get some onscreen information including memory usage. Are you talking about that? \n\nPlease be aware that even uncompressed chunks dont require very much memory, approximately 163 KB per chunk. Even if you would have 100 chunks in memory, that would only require 16 MB! And in the current implementation that only happens when you walk around enough to generate 100 chunks. When you quit and restart the game, these chunks are NOT in memory, they are loaded at demand.\n\nWhen you press F3 the number that matters the most for you is \"mem usage\". This number grows steadily and then suddenly drops again. Thats because the game creates lots of temporary objects which are garbage collected in cycles. When you have a couple of hundred chunks in memory you can see that the number grows slower if sparse chunks are used.\n\nIt's difficult to measure that precisely....\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2013-01-01T23:06:29Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-01-01T23:06:29Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I've actually defined a protobuf format for chunks as part of the multiplayer work I'm doing, but it only covers dense chunks so far (essentially your work is going to break my net code for chunks, but that is unavoidable). Ultimately I would see a protobuf format replacing the existing method.\n\nOn the benchmarking, I haven't checked your code thoroughly but one thing you should consider: a general recommendation I've seen for benchmarking is to have a warm up period where a certain number of iterations are run (at least a few hundred) before starting to record results, in order to try ensure the JIT optimisation has been done prior. This would help with what you are reporting regarding running multiple tests in a single run, and produce better results anyway.\n\nFor memory usage, I like to think about this in terms of number of players the server can support. Each player needs all the relevant chunks around them are kept in memory (for simulation and immediate usage). If the players are spread out, then these relevance regions are distinct. The current \"ultra\" view distance setting is 48, meaning 48_48 chunks are required (hmm, I wonder if the camera far distance is long enough to support that at the moment) - 2304 chunks. Each chunk is 16_16*256 blocks, using 3 bytes a block (soon to be 4 when we switch to using shorts for block ids). This would means 262KB per dense chunk, and 603MB per player - so 3 players on a server with 2GB of memory. This is kind of a ridiculously small number of players. Now the player views in a circle, so a circle of chunks is probably more relevant (or a sphere given a 3D grid of chunks), and perhaps view distance of 48 is simply too large for multiplayer.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@holy12345 @qiangdavidliu \r\nI have added test case for this scenario, please review my code. Many thanks.\r\n\r\nI will clarify briefly about what I have done. I create a new testcase named `TimeConsumingInstanceRegistryTest.java` which will run a bunch of sequential events in 2 minutes. I have added detailed comments about the steps that will be executed. \r\nHere I will paste them out for you to take a look.\r\n```\r\nVerify the following behaviors, the test case will run for 2 minutes.\r\n1. Registration of new instances.\r\n2. Lease expiration.\r\n3. NumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold will be updated. Since this threshold will be updated according to EurekaServerConfig.getRenewalThresholdUpdateIntervalMs(), and discovery client will try to get applications count from peer or remote Eureka servers, the count number will be used to update threshold.\r\nBelow shows the time line of a bunch of events in 120 seconds. Here the following setting are configured during registry startup: eureka.renewalThresholdUpdateIntervalMs=5000, eureka.evictionIntervalTimerInMs=10000\r\n       TimeInSecs 0          15         30    40   45         60        75   80      90         105       120\r\n                  |----------|----------|------|----|----------|---------|----|-------|----------|---------|\r\n       Events    (1)        (2)               (3)  (4)        (5)       (6)  (7)                (8)       (9)\r\n       \r\n(1). Remote server started on random port, local registry started as well. 50 instances will be registered to local registry with application name of LOCAL_REGION_APP_NAME and lease duration set to 30 seconds. At this time isLeaseExpirationEnabled=false, getNumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold= (50*2 + 1(initial value))*85%=86\r\n(2). 45 out of the 50 instances send heartbeats to local registry.\r\n(3). Check registry status, isLeaseExpirationEnabled=false, getNumOfRenewsInLastMin=0, getNumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold=86, registeredInstancesNumberOfMYLOCALAPP=50\r\n(4). 45 out of the 50 instances send heartbeats to local registry.\r\n(5). Accumulate one minutes data, and from now on, isLeaseExpirationEnabled=true, getNumOfRenewsInLastMin=90. Because lease expiration is enabled, and lease for 5 instance are expired, so evict 5 instances.\r\n(6). 45 out of the 50 instances send heartbeats to local registry.\r\n(7). Check registry status, isLeaseExpirationEnabled=true, getNumOfRenewsInLastMin=90, getNumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold=86, registeredInstancesNumberOfMYLOCALAPP=45\r\nRemote region add another 150 instances to application of LOCAL_REGION_APP_NAME. This will make PeerAwareInstanceRegistryImpl.updateRenewalThreshold() to refresh AbstractInstanceRegistry.numberOfRenewsPerMinThreshold.\r\n(8). 45 out of the 50 instances send heartbeats to local registry.\r\n(9). Check registry status, isLeaseExpirationEnabled=false, getNumOfRenewsInLastMin=90, getNumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold=256, registeredInstancesNumberOfMYLOCALAPP=45\r\nNote that there is a thread retrieving and printing out registry status for debugging purpose.\r\n```\r\n\r\nAfter reviewing the history of method `updateRenewalThreshold()`. I assume the logic is for the following scenario.\r\nAssuming there are 2 servers, server-A and server-B, each has total 100 heartbeats expected, and expiration threshold is 85. After sometime, server-A becomes an isolated island, losting connection with all clients and peer server-B. Then server-A enables preservation mode to avoid evict many instances. After a while when connection comes back to normal, it finds there are total 200 heartbeats expected from server-B which satisfy the condition of `updateRenewalThreshold()`, if the count is bigger than `85% * numberOfRenewsPerMinThreshold`, then server-A will update its renewal threshold to 170 as what server-B does. And after a while with new heartbeats to server-B and replicating to server-A, server-A will catch up and eventually the two servers are consistent.\r\n@qiangdavidliu could you help me review the case? or if you have more insights. Thanks!",

    "updated_at": "2018-05-25T16:53:29Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@holy12345 As far as I know, Eureka will update `numberOfRenewsPerMinThreshold` in 4 cases:\r\n* Register new instance.\r\n* Cancel one instance proactively.\r\n* Eureka server opening for traffic and this value is the number of instances replicated from peer.\r\n* In `updateRenewalThreshold()` method where it will be updated in 15mins in background.\r\n\r\nBut in expired cases, the value will not be updated since self-preservation relies on the value to determine if heartbeats drop below 85% of the expected number, so Eureka should not update this value when removing expired instances.",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2018-06-23T16:33:28Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-06-23T16:33:28Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@mattnelson In normal case, `updateRenewalThreshold` will only be updated when adding or dropping instances, if self perseveration is enabled, then if the heartbeats from instances drop below 85% of the expected value, eureka server stops to expire instance and will not quit unless the lost instances are back online to register/renew with eureka server. \r\nEureka will also try to get applications from peers, if the count is bigger than the threshold, it will update the `updateRenewalThreshold` of itself, this is what this PR works on to adjust and clarify.\r\nIn my opinion, if Eureka enters self preservation mode, and you deliberately offline some servers, Eureka will not quit. ",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@holy12345 @qiangdavidliu \r\nI have added test case for this scenario, please review my code. Many thanks.\r\n\r\nI will clarify briefly about what I have done. I create a new testcase named `TimeConsumingInstanceRegistryTest.java` which will run a bunch of sequential events in 2 minutes. I have added detailed comments about the steps that will be executed. \r\nHere I will paste them out for you to take a look.\r\n```\r\nVerify the following behaviors, the test case will run for 2 minutes.\r\n1. Registration of new instances.\r\n2. Lease expiration.\r\n3. NumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold will be updated. Since this threshold will be updated according to EurekaServerConfig.getRenewalThresholdUpdateIntervalMs(), and discovery client will try to get applications count from peer or remote Eureka servers, the count number will be used to update threshold.\r\nBelow shows the time line of a bunch of events in 120 seconds. Here the following setting are configured during registry startup: eureka.renewalThresholdUpdateIntervalMs=5000, eureka.evictionIntervalTimerInMs=10000\r\n       TimeInSecs 0          15         30    40   45         60        75   80      90         105       120\r\n                  |----------|----------|------|----|----------|---------|----|-------|----------|---------|\r\n       Events    (1)        (2)               (3)  (4)        (5)       (6)  (7)                (8)       (9)\r\n       \r\n(1). Remote server started on random port, local registry started as well. 50 instances will be registered to local registry with application name of LOCAL_REGION_APP_NAME and lease duration set to 30 seconds. At this time isLeaseExpirationEnabled=false, getNumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold= (50*2 + 1(initial value))*85%=86\r\n(2). 45 out of the 50 instances send heartbeats to local registry.\r\n(3). Check registry status, isLeaseExpirationEnabled=false, getNumOfRenewsInLastMin=0, getNumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold=86, registeredInstancesNumberOfMYLOCALAPP=50\r\n(4). 45 out of the 50 instances send heartbeats to local registry.\r\n(5). Accumulate one minutes data, and from now on, isLeaseExpirationEnabled=true, getNumOfRenewsInLastMin=90. Because lease expiration is enabled, and lease for 5 instance are expired, so evict 5 instances.\r\n(6). 45 out of the 50 instances send heartbeats to local registry.\r\n(7). Check registry status, isLeaseExpirationEnabled=true, getNumOfRenewsInLastMin=90, getNumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold=86, registeredInstancesNumberOfMYLOCALAPP=45\r\nRemote region add another 150 instances to application of LOCAL_REGION_APP_NAME. This will make PeerAwareInstanceRegistryImpl.updateRenewalThreshold() to refresh AbstractInstanceRegistry.numberOfRenewsPerMinThreshold.\r\n(8). 45 out of the 50 instances send heartbeats to local registry.\r\n(9). Check registry status, isLeaseExpirationEnabled=false, getNumOfRenewsInLastMin=90, getNumOfRenewsPerMinThreshold=256, registeredInstancesNumberOfMYLOCALAPP=45\r\nNote that there is a thread retrieving and printing out registry status for debugging purpose.\r\n```\r\n\r\nAfter reviewing the history of method `updateRenewalThreshold()`. I assume the logic is for the following scenario.\r\nAssuming there are 2 servers, server-A and server-B, each has total 100 heartbeats expected, and expiration threshold is 85. After sometime, server-A becomes an isolated island, losting connection with all clients and peer server-B. Then server-A enables preservation mode to avoid evict many instances. After a while when connection comes back to normal, it finds there are total 200 heartbeats expected from server-B which satisfy the condition of `updateRenewalThreshold()`, if the count is bigger than `85% * numberOfRenewsPerMinThreshold`, then server-A will update its renewal threshold to 170 as what server-B does. And after a while with new heartbeats to server-B and replicating to server-A, server-A will catch up and eventually the two servers are consistent.\r\n@qiangdavidliu could you help me review the case? or if you have more insights. Thanks!",

    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@holy12345 As far as I know, Eureka will update `numberOfRenewsPerMinThreshold` in 4 cases:\r\n* Register new instance.\r\n* Cancel one instance proactively.\r\n* Eureka server opening for traffic and this value is the number of instances replicated from peer.\r\n* In `updateRenewalThreshold()` method where it will be updated in 15mins in background.\r\n\r\nBut in expired cases, the value will not be updated since self-preservation relies on the value to determine if heartbeats drop below 85% of the expected number, so Eureka should not update this value when removing expired instances.",

    "created_at": "2018-06-23T16:33:28Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-06-23T16:33:28Z",
    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "@mattnelson In normal case, `updateRenewalThreshold` will only be updated when adding or dropping instances, if self perseveration is enabled, then if the heartbeats from instances drop below 85% of the expected value, eureka server stops to expire instance and will not quit unless the lost instances are back online to register/renew with eureka server. \r\nEureka will also try to get applications from peers, if the count is bigger than the threshold, it will update the `updateRenewalThreshold` of itself, this is what this PR works on to adjust and clarify.\r\nIn my opinion, if Eureka enters self preservation mode, and you deliberately offline some servers, Eureka will not quit. ",

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@tfmorris this schema module is the equivalent of the \"protograph\" or skeleton in Freebase terms: it's an expression that can be evaluated into the Wikibase data model. So you cannot reuse classes for the data model itself: you need to be able to represent variables (columns), and serialize them as such (to store the schema as an overlay model).\r\n\r\nThat being said, I do think some of the classes introduced in this extension could eventually make it into Wikidata-Toolkit (the maintainer is keen).",

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@tfmorris this schema module is the equivalent of the \"protograph\" or skeleton in Freebase terms: it's an expression that can be evaluated into the Wikibase data model. So you cannot reuse classes for the data model itself: you need to be able to represent variables (columns), and serialize them as such (to store the schema as an overlay model).\r\n\r\nThat being said, I do think some of the classes introduced in this extension could eventually make it into Wikidata-Toolkit (the maintainer is keen).",

    "body": "@thadguidry I value your feedback very much, I think you always make very good points as a user. As I have said before, I think you should leave the programming side of PR reviews to programmers (and not merge any PR that involves a code change without the approval of someone who contributes to the code). Codacy is nice, but you need to understand what is going on in the code to take advantage of its warnings.     "updated_at": "2018-04-05T06:17:47Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Well in OAuth it is always possible for a provider to revoke the application credentials (the ones that you have put in the source code) if these credentials are misused - typically if they are reused in another application for malicious purposes. I know you have not found anything in the docs about that, but that is just how OAuth works in general. That's why I would be in favour of changing the tokens before the release - the tokens you put in the packaged versions will not be as visible as the ones in the source code. As I said before, I think this is quite important, otherwise we will be quite vulnerable.",

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@jackyq2015 here is what I propose:\r\nWhen building the packaged versions of OpenRefine (when we make a release), we change the OAuth tokens (without committing that change to git). In this way, the compiled jars contain a different API key than the one that is on GitHub. It is still possible to extract these API keys from the jars and classes, but these keys are not as visible as the one that is on GitHub.\r\n\r\nIf Google is not happy about this API key being distributed publicly on GitHub, I would not be surprised if they revoke that key - but that would not affect the users because they would be using a different key.\r\n\r\nIs that clearer?",

    "created_at": "2018-04-05T06:16:30Z",
    "updated_at": "2018-04-05T06:17:47Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Well in OAuth it is always possible for a provider to revoke the application credentials (the ones that you have put in the source code) if these credentials are misused - typically if they are reused in another application for malicious purposes. I know you have not found anything in the docs about that, but that is just how OAuth works in general. That's why I would be in favour of changing the tokens before the release - the tokens you put in the packaged versions will not be as visible as the ones in the source code. As I said before, I think this is quite important, otherwise we will be quite vulnerable.",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "@jackyq2015 here is what I propose:\r\nWhen building the packaged versions of OpenRefine (when we make a release), we change the OAuth tokens (without committing that change to git). In this way, the compiled jars contain a different API key than the one that is on GitHub. It is still possible to extract these API keys from the jars and classes, but these keys are not as visible as the one that is on GitHub.\r\n\r\nIf Google is not happy about this API key being distributed publicly on GitHub, I would not be surprised if they revoke that key - but that would not affect the users because they would be using a different key.\r\n\r\nIs that clearer?",

    "body": "the origin function is:\n\n```\nprotected ShaderVar getReturnTypeForOperation(DataType left, DataType right)\n    {\n        ShaderVar out = null;\n\n        if(left == right)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(left);\n        else if(left == DataType.IVEC4 || right == DataType.IVEC4)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.IVEC4);\n        else if(left == DataType.IVEC3 || right == DataType.IVEC3)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.IVEC3);\n        else if(left == DataType.IVEC2 || right == DataType.IVEC2)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.IVEC2);\n        else if(left == DataType.VEC4 || right == DataType.VEC4)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.VEC4);\n        else if(left == DataType.VEC3 || right == DataType.VEC3)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.VEC3);\n        else if(left == DataType.VEC2 || right == DataType.VEC2)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.VEC2);\n        else if(left == DataType.MAT4 || right == DataType.MAT4)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.MAT4);\n        else if(left == DataType.MAT3 || right == DataType.MAT3)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.MAT3);\n        else if(left == DataType.MAT2 || right == DataType.MAT2)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.MAT2);\n        else if(left == DataType.FLOAT || right == DataType.FLOAT)\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.FLOAT);\n        else\n            out = getInstanceForDataType(DataType.INT);\n\n        return out;\n    }\n```\n\nat first use `if (left == right)`, then like this `else if(left == DataType.IVEC4 || right == DataType.IVEC4)`  will not run. So i think this code have problem.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

    "created_at": "2013-03-13T12:58:32Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-03-13T12:58:32Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I do have method overload for converting a regular Bitmap to ETC1 on-the-fly. If you look at [TextureManager.java line 310](https://github.com/MasDennis/Rajawali/blob/master/src/rajawali/materials/TextureManager.java#L310), I added a helper method that will take your `Bitmap` and compress it to ETC1. However, if you want seemless user experience, I highly discourage it as it will take quite a while to process especially on older phones unless you were compressing texture smaller than 512x512 (512x512 texture even takes about 20-30 seconds to compress on my desktop PC using Mali Texture Compression Tool). \n\nAnd yes, ETC1 does not support alpha. It is best used for opaque diffuse textures or specular maps. [Mali Texture Compression Tool](http://malideveloper.arm.com/develop-for-mali/mali-gpu-texture-compression-tool/) actually allows you to create alpha maps from your PNG/GIF images. Still, this is way more efficient than a single PNG decompressed into your GPU memory.\n\nIf you are targeting a specific device you may want to look at other texture compression formats other than ETC1 but you're on your own for writing helper methods for reading in those formats.\n\nComparison with 2048x1024 texture:\n- PNG with alpha channel (uncompressed as RGBA8888 in memory) : 6MB\n- Single ETC1 without alpha map : 1MB\n- ETC1 with alpha map (two textures) : 2MB\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "created_at": "2013-03-13T12:58:32Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-03-13T12:58:32Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I do have method overload for converting a regular Bitmap to ETC1 on-the-fly. If you look at [TextureManager.java line 310](https://github.com/MasDennis/Rajawali/blob/master/src/rajawali/materials/TextureManager.java#L310), I added a helper method that will take your `Bitmap` and compress it to ETC1. However, if you want seemless user experience, I highly discourage it as it will take quite a while to process especially on older phones unless you were compressing texture smaller than 512x512 (512x512 texture even takes about 20-30 seconds to compress on my desktop PC using Mali Texture Compression Tool). \n\nAnd yes, ETC1 does not support alpha. It is best used for opaque diffuse textures or specular maps. [Mali Texture Compression Tool](http://malideveloper.arm.com/develop-for-mali/mali-gpu-texture-compression-tool/) actually allows you to create alpha maps from your PNG/GIF images. Still, this is way more efficient than a single PNG decompressed into your GPU memory.\n\nIf you are targeting a specific device you may want to look at other texture compression formats other than ETC1 but you're on your own for writing helper methods for reading in those formats.\n\nComparison with 2048x1024 texture:\n- PNG with alpha channel (uncompressed as RGBA8888 in memory) : 6MB\n- Single ETC1 without alpha map : 1MB\n- ETC1 with alpha map (two textures) : 2MB\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "created_at": "2013-03-13T12:58:32Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-03-13T12:58:32Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I do have method overload for converting a regular Bitmap to ETC1 on-the-fly. If you look at [TextureManager.java line 310](https://github.com/MasDennis/Rajawali/blob/master/src/rajawali/materials/TextureManager.java#L310), I added a helper method that will take your `Bitmap` and compress it to ETC1. However, if you want seemless user experience, I highly discourage it as it will take quite a while to process especially on older phones unless you were compressing texture smaller than 512x512 (512x512 texture even takes about 20-30 seconds to compress on my desktop PC using Mali Texture Compression Tool). \n\nAnd yes, ETC1 does not support alpha. It is best used for opaque diffuse textures or specular maps. [Mali Texture Compression Tool](http://malideveloper.arm.com/develop-for-mali/mali-gpu-texture-compression-tool/) actually allows you to create alpha maps from your PNG/GIF images. Still, this is way more efficient than a single PNG decompressed into your GPU memory.\n\nIf you are targeting a specific device you may want to look at other texture compression formats other than ETC1 but you're on your own for writing helper methods for reading in those formats.\n\nComparison with 2048x1024 texture:\n- PNG with alpha channel (uncompressed as RGBA8888 in memory) : 6MB\n- Single ETC1 without alpha map : 1MB\n- ETC1 with alpha map (two textures) : 2MB\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

    "created_at": "2013-03-13T12:58:32Z",
    "updated_at": "2013-03-13T12:58:32Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I do have method overload for converting a regular Bitmap to ETC1 on-the-fly. If you look at [TextureManager.java line 310](https://github.com/MasDennis/Rajawali/blob/master/src/rajawali/materials/TextureManager.java#L310), I added a helper method that will take your `Bitmap` and compress it to ETC1. However, if you want seemless user experience, I highly discourage it as it will take quite a while to process especially on older phones unless you were compressing texture smaller than 512x512 (512x512 texture even takes about 20-30 seconds to compress on my desktop PC using Mali Texture Compression Tool). \n\nAnd yes, ETC1 does not support alpha. It is best used for opaque diffuse textures or specular maps. [Mali Texture Compression Tool](http://malideveloper.arm.com/develop-for-mali/mali-gpu-texture-compression-tool/) actually allows you to create alpha maps from your PNG/GIF images. Still, this is way more efficient than a single PNG decompressed into your GPU memory.\n\nIf you are targeting a specific device you may want to look at other texture compression formats other than ETC1 but you're on your own for writing helper methods for reading in those formats.\n\nComparison with 2048x1024 texture:\n- PNG with alpha channel (uncompressed as RGBA8888 in memory) : 6MB\n- Single ETC1 without alpha map : 1MB\n- ETC1 with alpha map (two textures) : 2MB\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  },

If I remove the interrupt check from poll, any-sized testParallel passes.\n\nSemaphore + queue with permits and batch drain of the queue, [code](https://gist.github.com/akarnokd/8863449)\n\n1:       95 000 ops/s\n2:      272 000 ops/s\n4:      900 000 ops/s\n8:    1 900 000 ops/s\n16:   3 074 000 ops/s\n32:   5 400 000 ops/s\n64:   8 700 000 ops/s\n128:  7 700 000 ops/s\n256:  7 600 000 ops/s\n512: 11 086 000 ops/s\n\nUsing batch drain appears to be more efficient when the queue size > 16 on my machine. I think the reason for this is that permits are released in larger numbers and producers less frequently need to wait for a 0 -> 1 permit transition.\nGoing above 512 resulted in significant fluctuations between 8M - 13M.\n\nThe two latter TransferQueue based implementations fluctuate quite a bit between 600k - 1200k for some reason. (Tested on i7 920 @ 2.66GHz, Win7x64, 6GB DDR3&1333MHz, Java 7 u51 x64).\n\nI tried to improve performance of the 1 permit case via TransferQueue, but I couldn't get reliable data exchange nor could I implement proper interruption.\n",

    "updated_at": "2014-02-17T16:31:09Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I've been playing with this over the weekend with 0.17.0-RC1 and think we need to revert the default back-pressure behavior. I think it is relevant as an option to be applied, but it's too risky as the default behavior if the source `Observable` is being emitted from an event loop (such as an NIO selector thread).\n\nI'm going to submit a change today that splits out `OperatorObserveOn` and `OperatorObserveOnBounded` and leaves the default `observeOn(Scheduler s)` using the unbounded version.\n\nFurther discussion of providing tools for back-pressure will be picked up in the 0.18 dev cycle.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null

If I remove the interrupt check from poll, any-sized testParallel passes.\n\nSemaphore + queue with permits and batch drain of the queue, [code](https://gist.github.com/akarnokd/8863449)\n\n1:       95 000 ops/s\n2:      272 000 ops/s\n4:      900 000 ops/s\n8:    1 900 000 ops/s\n16:   3 074 000 ops/s\n32:   5 400 000 ops/s\n64:   8 700 000 ops/s\n128:  7 700 000 ops/s\n256:  7 600 000 ops/s\n512: 11 086 000 ops/s\n\nUsing batch drain appears to be more efficient when the queue size > 16 on my machine. I think the reason for this is that permits are released in larger numbers and producers less frequently need to wait for a 0 -> 1 permit transition.\nGoing above 512 resulted in significant fluctuations between 8M - 13M.\n\nThe two latter TransferQueue based implementations fluctuate quite a bit between 600k - 1200k for some reason. (Tested on i7 920 @ 2.66GHz, Win7x64, 6GB DDR3&1333MHz, Java 7 u51 x64).\n\nI tried to improve performance of the 1 permit case via TransferQueue, but I couldn't get reliable data exchange nor could I implement proper interruption.\n",

    "created_at": "2014-02-17T16:31:09Z",
    "updated_at": "2014-02-17T16:31:09Z",
    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "I've been playing with this over the weekend with 0.17.0-RC1 and think we need to revert the default back-pressure behavior. I think it is relevant as an option to be applied, but it's too risky as the default behavior if the source `Observable` is being emitted from an event loop (such as an NIO selector thread).\n\nI'm going to submit a change today that splits out `OperatorObserveOn` and `OperatorObserveOnBounded` and leaves the default `observeOn(Scheduler s)` using the unbounded version.\n\nFurther discussion of providing tools for back-pressure will be picked up in the 0.18 dev cycle.\n",
    "performed_via_github_app": null
  }
